### 1. One-Line Summary
* Nittaku G-1: A high-grip, high-arc ESN-style rubber that rewards full strokes with heavy spin and stable counter-looping.
* Rakza Z: A tacky-hybrid rubber that excels at first-ball spin and controlled power, with a lower, more direct trajectory.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rakza Z feels livelier/easier to keep short and spinny with compact swings; G-1 can feel a bit “dead” unless you engage the sponge.
    * **Top End:** G-1 has the higher ceiling when you swing big (especially mid-distance); Rakza Z tops out earlier but stays controlled.
    * **Linearity:** Rakza Z is more linear and predictable across gears; G-1 has a clearer jump when you compress the sponge hard.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Rakza Z is superior for lifting heavy backspin with a shorter stroke due to tack + dwell; G-1 is excellent but prefers more acceleration and forward brush.
    * **Max Spin:** Very close; G-1 often wins on “pure” high-speed brush spin in rallies, while Rakza Z produces heavier, slower “loaded” spin that drops faster.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Rakza Z has tacky + grippy behavior (strong at slow contact); G-1 is very grippy (strong at high friction, high-speed contact) but not tacky.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** G-1 generally throws higher with a rounder arc; Rakza Z is lower-to-medium with a more direct line.
    * **Safety:** G-1 provides more net clearance and rally safety; Rakza Z is safe when you brush well, but demands cleaner timing/angle on flatter hits.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** G-1 feels firmer/crisper and more “ESN tensor-like”; Rakza Z feels denser and more “hybrid,” with a slightly muted tacky topsheet sensation.
    * **Dwell:** Rakza Z holds the ball longer at low-medium impact; G-1’s dwell becomes more apparent when you engage sponge strongly.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** G-1 is more reactive to incoming spin in serve receive and touch; Rakza Z’s tacky topsheet can reduce “pop” and help keep the ball short, but it can also grab spin if your angle is late.
    * **Touch Play:** Rakza Z usually has the edge for stop, short push, and heavy/slow spinny serves; G-1 is solid but more bouncy once engaged.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rakza Z is steadier and lower-throw on passive blocks; G-1’s higher throw can float long unless you close the angle.
    * **Active Counter:** G-1 shines on counter-looping and punchy topspin counters; Rakza Z is reliable and controlled but less explosive at high pace.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Nittaku G-1 if:**
    * You play a topspin-to-topspin game and want a higher arc with strong counter-loop stability.
    * You swing big (forehand or backhand) and need a higher top-end from mid-distance.
    * You prefer a crisp, direct feedback rubber for aggressive rallying.

* **Choose Rakza Z if:**
    * Your game is first-ball focused (serve + third ball) and you value easy opening against backspin.
    * You want a tacky-hybrid feel that supports short game control and heavy, slower spin.
    * You prefer linear power and a lower, more direct trajectory for blocks and controlled counters.